The final confrontation.
She is stationary — connected to the Eye, she cannot move. This is the only moment in the campaign where her Agility 6 is a genuine tactical vulnerability. She has built the College around it. The pre-built architecture is extensive, layered, and designed by someone who has had 4,000 years to think about geometry and has known for three adventures this moment was coming.
Her combat priority:
Maintain the transfer. Do not break contact with the Eye for any reason.
Anyone targeting the Crown during the flux window gets Ice-Destruction immediately. She has been thinking about this. She knows what they know.
Skyrim's Cold for grouping. She cannot move. She uses area denial.
The Khajiit. Even now. Even here. She cannot process this cleanly and she has stopped pretending she can. She will freeze their emotions — she cannot make herself destroy them — and return immediately to the transfer. Everyone at the table should see this happen.
The Dragon Cult: Also here. Also wanting the transfer stopped. Their method destroys the Eye, which produces a different ending than the disruption. The party manages both simultaneously.
What the party needs to win: Knowledge of the resonance window from Frostmere. Access to the Crown during the flux. Whatever power they've built — Daedric assistance, Divine intervention, the Cult's records, something they invented from five adventures of paying attention.
The combat system alone is not sufficient. That is correct. That is the design.

