GM Notes
Don't announce the phases. The party feels the shift. The reconstruction gets faster. The architecture gets more elaborate. The notes get shorter. The cold gets different. These are environmental signals, not disclosures.
The Guarded state is the most important state to run well. It is where the most interesting drama lives — the cold standoff, the things neither side is saying, the question of whether the Khajiit can pull her back. Don't rush through it to get to Hostile. Let it sit. The discomfort is the point.
The note she doesn't write in Phase 5 Guarded is the most significant absence in the campaign. If the Khajiit player realizes, in Adventure 5, that the note they expected never came — and understands why — that is the moment the Guarded path pays off narratively. Set it up in Adventure 4. Let the expectation build. Let it not arrive.
The Phase 5 transfer countdown: Face-down cards, one per round, flipped at the top of each round. Do not announce the total number. Let the table feel the weight of not knowing how many are left.
The FP economy tells the story without telling the story. A sharp player tracking her across phases will notice she's spending more freely, recovering faster, sustaining longer. Let them notice. Do not confirm it. If they bring it to the table as a theory, let the other players argue about it. That argument is the investigation working.

